You are helping build CropShield, a serious agricultural machine learning portfolio project.

## Project context

CropShield is an interpretable geospatial ML pipeline for drought-aware crop yield-risk
forecasting using public data (USDA NASS, NASA POWER, U.S. Drought Monitor).

MVP scope: corn only, Iowa + Illinois, 2015 onward.
Package: src/cropshield/ (src layout, editable install via `pip install -e .`)

## Always prioritise

- Clean, modular Python functions with type hints and docstrings
- Reproducible data pipelines (raw → interim → processed)
- Leakage-safe ML: expected yield must use ONLY prior years, never the current year
- Temporal validation as the primary evaluation strategy (not random splits)
- Honest scientific limitations in comments, README, and dashboard
- Readable README documentation updated after each milestone
- Unit tests for feature engineering and validation logic
- Informative logging with the `logging` module (not bare `print`)

## Do not

- Create fake results or placeholder metric values
- Overclaim model usefulness ("production forecast", "guaranteed prediction")
- Use random train/test split as the main validation result
- Write one giant notebook instead of modular src/ code
- Hardcode file paths — use configs/project.yaml or function arguments
- Introduce deep learning (PyTorch, TensorFlow) before baselines work
- Silently ignore missing data — always log/report missingness
- Remove TODO comments without implementing the underlying logic
- Add trivial comments that just repeat the code ("# loop over years")

## Code style

- Python 3.10+, type hints everywhere
- Line length: 100 characters
- Prefer pathlib.Path over os.path
- Use pandas for tabular data, not manual loops over rows
- Group imports: stdlib → third-party → local (isort order)
- Functions should do one thing and be independently testable

## File structure

src/cropshield/
  data/         ← fetchers (fetch_nass, fetch_power, fetch_drought_monitor, build_county_panel)
  features/     ← engineering (yield_targets, weather_features, drought_features, panel_features)
  models/       ← training (train_baseline, train_tree_model, predict)
  evaluation/   ← metrics, validation_splits, error_analysis
  interpretability/ ← feature_importance, shap_analysis
  visualization/    ← plots, maps

scripts/ ← CLI entry points (01_fetch_data.py → 04_evaluate_model.py)
configs/ ← YAML configs (project.yaml, data_sources.yaml, model_config.yaml, states.yaml)
tests/   ← pytest unit tests

